  "body": "Hello,\r\n\r\nI have been experimenting with a Dockerfile workflow for use in the workshops which would build a base nethermind image compiled from source and then run a spaceneth node  (as in the `all platforms` section of the docs). Here is the docker file which I created (named `Dockerfile_workshop`)\r\n\r\n```\r\nFROM microsoft/dotnet:2.2-sdk AS build\r\nCOPY . .\r\nRUN git submodule update --init\r\nRUN apt-get update && apt-get -y install libsnappy-dev libc6-dev libc6 unzip\r\nRUN cd src/Nethermind && dotnet build Nethermind.sln -c Release\r\n\r\nEXPOSE 8345 30312\r\n\r\nWORKDIR src/Nethermind\r\n```\r\n\r\nand then to start the container instance I run\r\n\r\n```\r\ngit clone https://github.com/nethermindeth/nethermind nethworkshop --recursive -b workshop\r\ncd nethworkshop\r\n\r\n```\r\n\r\nAnd to attach a shell in the container \r\nFinally, the user can continue in the all platforms section but skip the first part of cloning the repository. The only additional step is to start a new terminal one needs to run the following command to attach to the container shell:\r\n\r\n```\r\ndocker exec -it bin \r\n```\r\n\r\nIf you think this is useful for your upcoming workshops I can create a PR for it @tkstanczak ",
